This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for local declaration ordering.

## Core concept

A topological sort turns a dependency graph into an order where each local declaration is ready before its consumer.

## Beanstalk boundary

Stage 3 orders declarations owned by one canonical module. Stage 0 has already ordered provider modules and packages.

It uses only local declaration edges retained from header syntax. It does not:

- order project modules
- copy imported declarations into the graph
- inspect executable function bodies
- rebuild imports
- add a second semantic discovery pass

Same-file constant source order remains a language rule. Cross-file local dependencies use the retained graph.

## Rewrite focus

Explain directed acyclic graphs, cycle diagnostics, stable ordering among independent nodes and why body references do not belong in declaration ordering.

Canonical details live in `docs/compiler-design-overview.md`.
